---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const dirBody = `
  

  <!-- ============ SECTION 0: HERO ============ -->
  <header class="hero hero--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-text">
          <div class="hero-eyebrow eyebrow">Director-Band Executive Mortgages</div>
          <h1 class="display-1">Director-band mortgage from a lender who reads first RSU grants, annual bonus history, and promotion-track compensation.</h1>
          <p class="lead hero-subtitle">Directors, Senior Directors, and Senior Managers at public companies carry the compensation profile that&rsquo;s the most overlooked in corporate America: a base salary that&rsquo;s typically 55&ndash;70% of total comp (the highest base-share of any executive tier), restricted stock units (RSUs) often awarded for the first time at Director promotion, predictable annual cash bonuses tied to a documented formula, employee stock purchase plan (ESPP) participation as the entry point to equity comp, and a promotion track toward VP that fundamentally reshapes the qualifying picture every 3&ndash;5 years. Generalist lenders see the base salary and a small RSU vest and round down. We read the grant letter (often the first one in your career), the bonus formula, the ESPP detail, the 12-month vest history, and the promotion-track timing &mdash; and qualify you on the full picture including all the equity-comp pieces.</p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Talk to Our Team</a>
            <a href="#income-methods" class="btn btn-secondary btn-large">See how qualifying works</a>
          </div>
          <div class="hero-trust">
            <span class="trust-dot"></span>
            <span>Broker NMLS #1072866</span>
            <span>&middot;</span>
            <span>Specialist in Director-tier equity-comp &amp; first-time-RSU mortgages</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="hero-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/3184405/pexels-photo-3184405.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1200" alt="Corporate Director in modern office environment" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1200x1500/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Director+Band';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ============ STATS BAR ============ -->
  <section class="stats stats--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats-bar-grid">
        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$161K</div>
            <div class="stat-label">BLS financial managers May 2024 median (closest SOC to corporate Director-band)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">55&ndash;70%</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Base salary as % of Director total comp (vs 35-55% for SVP, 7-30% for C-suite)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">12 mo</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Time-based RSU vest history required by Fannie Mae for qualifying income</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">1</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Specialist who reads your first-time grant letter &amp; ESPP detail before we quote</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="stats-bar-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/1181263/pexels-photo-1181263.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1000" alt="Director collaborating with team in office meeting" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1000x750/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Director+Band';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ LEDE ============ -->
  <section class="lede-section">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <p class="lede">Stairway Mortgage qualifies Directors and Senior Managers on the full comp picture &mdash; <strong>including the equity-comp pieces that lenders trained on entry-level W-2 files often miss entirely</strong>. A newly-promoted Director with their first-ever RSU grant, an established Senior Director with three years of consistent vesting and a steady bonus history, a Senior Manager with deep ESPP participation building equity through the company stock plan, and a Director on the cusp of VP promotion managing the timing of a major home purchase each get qualified using the methods that fit their stage. We pick the right door before we quote. Or skip ahead: browse <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">every loan program</a>, run numbers on <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">100+ mortgage calculators</a>, or check <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/current-rates/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">today&apos;s rates</a>. For the parent hub and other executive paths, see our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">corporate executives mortgage hub</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #1: KEY FACTS ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">01 &middot; Director-band mortgage at a glance</div>
        <h2>Key facts every Director and Senior Manager should know before applying for a mortgage.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="key-facts-grid">
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">$161,700</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">BLS May 2024 median for financial managers (closest SOC to Director-band). Corporate Director total comp typically $180K&ndash;$450K. See <a href="https://www.bls.gov/ooh/management/financial-managers.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">BLS Financial Managers OOH</a> and <a href="https://www.bls.gov/ooh/management/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">BLS Management Occupations</a> ($122,090 median).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">12 months</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Time-based RSU vest history required by Fannie Mae before counting RSU income. <strong>This is often a binding constraint for newly-promoted Directors</strong> whose first RSU grant hasn&rsquo;t yet vested. See <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae Selling Guide B3-3.1-01</a>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">ESPP 15%</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Employee stock purchase plan discount (typically 15%, often with look-back pricing) reports as W-2 wage on qualifying-disposition years under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc427" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRS Topic 427</a>. Frequently overlooked at the Director tier where ESPP is often the largest equity-comp component.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">2-year bonus</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Annual cash bonus &mdash; typically 10&ndash;25% of Director total comp &mdash; qualifies on a <strong>two-year average</strong> under Fannie Mae variable-income rules. Documented via W-2 history, employment letter formula, and recent paystubs.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #2: ROLE-STAGE SOLUTIONS ============ -->
  <section class="professions-section section-tinted">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">02 &middot; Where you are in your Director-band tenure</div>
        <h2>Director-band mortgage solutions for every career stage.</h2>
        <p>Each Director-band stage has its own qualifying logic. A newly-promoted Director with a first-ever RSU grant has a different mortgage path than a Senior Director nearing VP promotion.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="professions-grid">

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">01</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Newly-promoted Director (Year 1)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Just promoted. First RSU grant ever. Year 1 of new comp structure."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Base $130K&ndash;$200K, first RSU grant not yet 12-month vested</li>
            <li>Qualifies on base + prior senior-individual-contributor W-2 with bonus history</li>
            <li>Conventional conforming dominant; bank-statement Non-QM rarely needed</li>
            <li>Plan to refinance after first vest unlocks the RSU income</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See newly-promoted Director mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">02</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Established Director (Years 2&ndash;4)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Director for 3 years. RSUs vesting annually. Predictable bonus."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Base $150K&ndash;$250K + $30K&ndash;$80K annual RSU vest + cash bonus</li>
            <li>Full RSU income qualifying with 24-month history (200-day MA)</li>
            <li>Conventional conforming with full base + RSU + bonus, sometimes low-jumbo</li>
            <li>ESPP discount adds incremental W-2 income on qualifying-disposition years</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See established Director mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">03</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Senior Director (Years 4&ndash;7)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Senior Director with team leadership. Larger annual RSU + bonus."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Base $200K&ndash;$320K + $50K&ndash;$140K annual RSU vest + cash bonus</li>
            <li>Conventional conforming or jumbo with three-year compensation history</li>
            <li>First-time jumbo borrower territory for many in this stage</li>
            <li>Sometimes paired with second home or rental property purchase</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See Senior Director mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">04</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Senior Manager / Director track (lateral)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Senior Manager / Principal-tier IC. Equity comp without direct reports."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Base $180K&ndash;$280K + meaningful RSU + cash bonus + ESPP</li>
            <li>Common in technology, financial services, healthcare</li>
            <li>Same qualifying frame as Director-band; documentation identical</li>
            <li>Strong reserves often support pledged-asset structures</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See Senior Manager mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">05</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Pre-VP / promotion-track (Years 5+)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Director close to VP promotion. Bigger home target on horizon."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Base + equity at top of Director band, VP promotion expected Year 1&ndash;2</li>
            <li>Timing decision: close now at current comp vs after promotion at higher comp</li>
            <li>Conforming or jumbo depending on target home price</li>
            <li>Refinance strategy when post-promotion comp has 12-month vest history</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See pre-VP mechanics</span>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #3: INCOME CALCULATION METHODS ============ -->
  <section class="section" id="income-methods">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">03 &middot; The qualification mechanics</div>
        <h2>How we calculate qualifying income for your Director-band mortgage.</h2>
        <p>Four methods cover almost every Director-band file we&rsquo;ve closed. The right method depends on whether you have 12-month RSU vest history, your bonus pattern, and whether equity comp is a meaningful part of your file or supplementary.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Method 1 &mdash; Base W-2 + annual cash bonus 2-year average (the Director-band default)</h3>
      <p>The dominant case for Director-band files. Base salary is W-2 wages. Annual cash bonus &mdash; typically 10&ndash;25% of total comp at this tier &mdash; qualifies on a two-year average under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae Selling Guide B3-3.1-01</a> variable-income rules. We document the bonus formula via your employment letter, the prior W-2s showing actual amounts, and the trend. This is the most common method at the Director tier because base is dominant and bonus is more predictable than at VP/SVP levels.</p>

      <h3>Method 2 &mdash; Base + RSU vest income (200-day moving average)</h3>
      <p>For Directors with 12+ months of time-based RSU vest history. Add RSU income calculated by taking vested shares over the trailing 12&ndash;24 months, valued at the <strong>200-day moving average</strong> of the company stock price. At the Director tier, RSU income is typically smaller in absolute terms than at VP/SVP, but it&rsquo;s often the difference between conventional conforming and conventional jumbo. We pull the brokerage statement, the vesting schedule, the grant letter (often the executive&rsquo;s first), and the W-2 to assemble this calculation.</p>

      <h3>Method 3 &mdash; ESPP qualifying-disposition income</h3>
      <p>For Directors and Senior Managers with deep ESPP participation. Under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc427" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRS Topic 427</a>, ESPP discount income (typically 15% discount with look-back pricing) reports as W-2 wage on qualifying-disposition years. For an executive contributing the IRS-max $25,000 annually to ESPP with 15% discount and look-back, the W-2 wage addback can be $5,000&ndash;$15,000+ annually. Generalist lenders often miss this entirely; it&rsquo;s already on the W-2 box 1 figure if they&rsquo;d read it.</p>

      <h3>Method 4 &mdash; Bank-statement (Non-QM) during promotion transition</h3>
      <p>For newly-promoted Directors without 12-month RSU vest history where the prior W-2 doesn&rsquo;t fully capture current comp. <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/43/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CFPB Reg Z&rsquo;s Ability-to-Repay rule</a> permits non-QM lending with compensating factors. We qualify on 12 or 24 months of personal bank deposits with an expense-ratio adjustment (typically 50&ndash;75% of deposits count). Less commonly used at the Director tier than at VP+ levels, but useful for promotion-window financing.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #4: DARK SECTION ============ -->
  <section class="per-diem-section per-diem-section--bg" style="background-image: url('https://images.pexels.com/photos/3184405/pexels-photo-3184405.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1800');">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="max-width: 760px;">
        <div class="eyebrow eyebrow-light">04 &middot; What generalist underwriting misses</div>
        <h2 style="color: var(--paper);">The income most lenders refuse to count on a Director-band file.</h2>
        <p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.78);">Six income components that show up consistently on Director-band files and that generalist lenders typically either ignore or mis-categorize. Each one is documentable; the lender just has to know what to ask for.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dark-grid">
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">A</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Annual cash bonus 2-year average (the big one at Director tier)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">At the Director tier, annual cash bonus is often <strong>more predictable and formula-driven</strong> than at VP/SVP levels, making it more reliable as qualifying income. With a two-year history, the bonus qualifies on the two-year average under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>. Generalist lenders often treat bonus as discretionary and exclude it &mdash; missing 15&ndash;25% of qualifying income.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">B</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">First-time RSU vest income</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">For Directors with their first-ever RSU grant, the income enters the qualifying picture once the 12-month time-based vest history matures. At the Director tier this RSU income is typically $30K&ndash;$100K annually &mdash; not the dominant comp line but often the difference between conforming and jumbo loan eligibility. We coordinate the mortgage timing with the vest event when possible.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">C</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">ESPP discount on qualifying-disposition years</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Many Directors and Senior Managers participate in ESPPs allowing purchase of company stock at a 15% discount with look-back pricing. Under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc427" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">IRS Topic 427</a>, the discount qualifies as W-2 wage in qualifying-disposition years. Generalist lenders frequently miss this $5,000&ndash;$15,000+ of additional W-2 income that&rsquo;s already on box 1.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">D</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">401(k) employer match &amp; profit-sharing</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Directors typically receive employer 401(k) match (often 4&ndash;6% of base) plus annual profit-sharing contributions ($10,000&ndash;$25,000). Under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/retirement-plans/plan-participant-employee/401k-resource-guide-plan-participants-general-distribution-rules" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">IRS 401(k) guidance</a>, these are deferred compensation documented on W-2 box 12. Not directly qualifying income, but they support the financial-strength narrative and reserves calculation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">E</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Sign-on bonus and relocation packages</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Directors recruited laterally often receive sign-on bonus payments ($25,000&ndash;$200,000) and relocation packages. The sign-on is one-time and doesn&rsquo;t qualify as continuing income; it does support down-payment funds if documented. <a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p521" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">IRS Publication 521</a> covers moving expense rules; the relocation gross-up appears on W-2 in the year received.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">F</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Overtime &amp; on-call differential (in eligible roles)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Some Director-band roles (especially in healthcare, IT operations, financial services trading) carry overtime or on-call pay differentials. These show on the W-2 alongside base. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae variable-income rules</a>, overtime with a two-year history qualifies on the two-year average. Underwriters often discount overtime; with proper documentation, the full average qualifies.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #5: LOAN PROGRAM MATRIX ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">05 &middot; Match the program to your Director stage</div>
        <h2>Which loan program fits your Director-band mortgage situation.</h2>
        <p>Seven loan-program categories cover essentially every Director-band purchase or refinance. The mix is heavily weighted toward conforming at this tier (less jumbo than SVP/VP, far less super-jumbo).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="loan-program-grid">

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Conventional Conforming</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Directors and Senior Directors with base + bonus + RSU income</li>
            <li>5&ndash;20% down, loan limits up to $766,550 (FL conforming) for 2024-25</li>
            <li>Best rates available; Fannie Mae or Freddie Mac underwriting</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Established Director-band tier</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">FHA</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Newly-promoted Directors with first home purchase</li>
            <li>3.5% down minimum, MIP for life of loan</li>
            <li>Useful when down payment is constrained or credit needs strengthening</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: First-time Director buyers</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">VA Loan</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Directors and Senior Managers with U.S. military service</li>
            <li>0% down, no PMI, rate competitive with conventional</li>
            <li>Strong overlap with Director-band tier in defense, healthcare</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Veteran Directors</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Conventional Jumbo</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Senior Directors and pre-VP track with base + equity above conforming</li>
            <li>10&ndash;20% down typical, $766,550&ndash;$1.5M loan range</li>
            <li>Rate often within 0.25% of conforming for clean files</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Senior Director / pre-VP track</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Bank-Statement Non-QM</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Newly-promoted Directors with comp ramping but no 12-month vest history</li>
            <li>12 or 24 months of personal deposits at 50&ndash;75% counting</li>
            <li>Rate 0.5&ndash;1.0% higher than conforming</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Promotion-window financing</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Pledged-Asset Loan</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Directors with significant ESPP/RSU stock accumulated</li>
            <li>Securities portfolio pledged against the mortgage</li>
            <li>Useful when concentrated stock position is too valuable to liquidate</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Long-tenure ESPP/RSU accumulators</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">USDA Rural</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Directors purchasing in USDA-eligible suburban or rural areas</li>
            <li>0% down, income limits apply (some Director files qualify)</li>
            <li>Many South Florida suburbs surprisingly USDA-eligible</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Suburban/rural Director purchases</div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #6: INDUSTRY CONTEXT ============ -->
  <section class="section section-tinted">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">06 &middot; Why this mortgage gets overlooked</div>
        <h2>The Director-band mortgage in context: 6 forces shaping how Directors qualify.</h2>
        <p>Director-band files are often mis-served not because the comp is exotic (it&rsquo;s not, relative to C-suite), but because lenders trained on entry-level W-2 underwriting don&rsquo;t pull the equity-comp pieces or read the bonus formula. The Director tier is the largest population in corporate-executive mortgages, and the most consistently under-quoted.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Force 1 &mdash; The first-time equity-comp borrower</h3>
      <p>Director promotion is typically when an employee receives their first-ever RSU grant. The borrower has no prior experience with equity comp on a mortgage file, and many lenders don&rsquo;t coach them on what to bring. We coach the file: grant letter, vesting schedule, brokerage statement, and confirmation that the 12-month vest history exists under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>. Done right, the first RSU vest year often unlocks meaningfully more loan capacity.</p>

      <h3>Force 2 &mdash; The base-to-equity ratio at Director tier</h3>
      <p>At Director, base salary is typically 55&ndash;70% of total comp &mdash; the highest base-share of any executive tier. Equity is 15&ndash;30%, cash bonus 10&ndash;25%, ESPP 2&ndash;5%. <a href="https://www.sec.gov/rules/final/2006/33-8732a.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SEC executive comp disclosure rules</a> require proxy reporting only for named executive officers (NEOs), so Director-band comp typically isn&rsquo;t in public filings. The <a href="https://www.federalreserve.gov/econres/scfindex.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Federal Reserve Survey of Consumer Finances</a> documents the wealth distribution at this tier. Each promotion step shifts the ratio significantly.</p>

      <h3>Force 3 &mdash; The 200-day moving average rule for RSU income</h3>
      <p>For RSU income calculation, Fannie Mae uses the <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">200-day moving average</a> of the company stock price; <a href="https://guide.freddiemac.com/app/guide/section/5303.4" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Freddie Mac</a> uses the 52-week average. Both methods smooth volatility but produce different qualifying numbers. At the Director tier where RSU income is smaller in absolute terms, the choice between Fannie and Freddie can swing qualifying income by $5K&ndash;$15K. We choose the favorable agency interpretation when available.</p>

      <h3>Force 4 &mdash; ESPP as the gateway equity-comp product</h3>
      <p>For many Directors, ESPP participation precedes RSU eligibility &mdash; the company stock plan available to all employees, often providing the first taste of equity-comp accumulation. Under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc427" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRS Topic 427</a>, ESPP discount income (typically 15% with look-back pricing) reports as W-2 wage in qualifying-disposition years. Deep ESPP participation also accumulates concentrated company stock that supports pledged-asset structures later.</p>

      <h3>Force 5 &mdash; 401(k) catch-up contributions and IRS limits</h3>
      <p>Directors over 50 can make catch-up contributions to 401(k) plans under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/retirement-plans/plan-participant-employee/retirement-topics-catch-up-contributions" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRS retirement catch-up rules</a> ($7,500 over the standard limit). For high-earning Directors who max out 401(k) plus catch-up, the W-2 box 1 figure is artificially depressed by $30,500&ndash;$31,000 versus actual cash compensation. We document the relationship between box 1 and total compensation so underwriters don&rsquo;t mistake aggressive retirement saving for low income.</p>

      <h3>Force 6 &mdash; The Director-to-VP promotion timing</h3>
      <p>Directors on a VP track typically advance every 3&ndash;5 years. The promotion brings: larger base, larger RSU grant (often 3&ndash;5&times; the Director-tier grant), larger annual bonus formula, sometimes a sign-on bonus and retention RSUs. Timing a mortgage close around the promotion is a real strategic question &mdash; close at current Director comp and refinance later, or wait until 12 months post-promotion to capture the new RSU history. We model both scenarios with the executive&rsquo;s promotion outlook.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

