      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto var(--s-8);">
        <div class="eyebrow">09 &middot; Director-band mortgage FAQs</div>
        <h2>Director-band mortgage questions, answered.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-list">

        <div class="faq-cross-links" style="margin-bottom: var(--s-10); padding: var(--s-6); background: var(--paper-warm); border-left: 3px solid var(--blue);">
          <p style="margin: 0 0 var(--s-3) 0; font-family: var(--serif); font-size: var(--text-md); font-weight: 500;">More <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">Director-band mortgage</a> resources at Stairway</p>
          <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: var(--s-5); font-size: var(--text-sm); line-height: 1.7; list-style: none;">
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/">All corporate executive mortgage programs</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/c-suite-executive/">C-Suite executive mortgage guide</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/senior-vp-vp/">Senior VP &amp; VP mortgage guide</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/pre-ipo-equity-holder/">Pre-IPO equity holder mortgage guide</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/relocating-executive/">Relocating executive mortgage guide</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/conventional-loan/">Conventional loan program details</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/jumbo-loan/">Jumbo loan program details</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/purchase-inquiry/">Start your Director-band mortgage pre-approval</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">01</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a newly-promoted Director with my first RSU grant. Can I use that income for a mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Not until 12 months of time-based vest history exists. Fannie Mae requires 12 months of RSU vesting before counting the income under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>. Until then, qualify on base + prior senior-IC W-2 with bonus. After the first vest, refinance to incorporate the new RSU income.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">02</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does Fannie Mae calculate RSU income at the Director tier?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Same as for VP/SVP/C-suite: take the dollar value of vested shares over trailing 12 or 24 months, valued at the <strong>200-day moving average</strong> of the company stock price. Divide by months in lookback for monthly qualifying figure. At the Director tier, RSU income is typically smaller in absolute terms ($30K&ndash;$100K annually) but proportionally significant.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">03</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My annual bonus is consistent but treated as "discretionary" by some lenders. What can I do?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Document the bonus formula via your employment letter or comp committee minutes. With a two-year history of bonus at consistent levels, the bonus qualifies on a two-year average under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>. Lenders that dismiss documented bonus as "discretionary" are misreading the rules.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">04</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Does ESPP participation help my mortgage application?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, in two ways. (1) The 15% ESPP discount reports as W-2 wage in qualifying-disposition years under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc427" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRS Topic 427</a> &mdash; this is already on your W-2 box 1 if you participate. (2) Accumulated ESPP stock supports reserves and pledged-asset structures. We document ESPP participation as part of the full file.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">05</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My company stock has declined. Does that affect my qualifying income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">If RSU income is part of your file, yes. Fannie Mae guidelines require conservative recalculation if year-to-date RSU income is more than 10% lower than the prior year. At the Director tier where RSU income is smaller, the impact is smaller in absolute terms but proportionally similar. We can sometimes pivot to <a href="https://guide.freddiemac.com/app/guide/section/5303.4" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Freddie Mac&rsquo;s 52-week average</a> for a better number.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">06</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m on a VP track and might be promoted soon. Should I wait to buy?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Depends on the home you want and the rate environment. If you&rsquo;re comfortable at your current Director comp, close now and refinance after promotion. If the target home requires the promoted comp, wait and time the mortgage 12&ndash;13 months after the VP role start (so the new RSU has 12-month vest history). We model both scenarios.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">07</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What documentation do I need to provide?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Typically: two years of W-2s, two years of federal 1040s with all schedules, RSU grant letters (all active grants), vesting schedule from your equity platform (Shareworks, Carta, E*TRADE), brokerage statements showing vested share value, ESPP participation detail if relevant, employment agreement including bonus formula, and recent paystubs.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I qualify for FHA at my Director income level?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">FHA has no income ceiling &mdash; the program is income-eligible regardless of pay. FHA has limits on loan size though. At the Director tier, FHA is useful primarily when down payment is constrained (3.5% min) or when credit needs strengthening. The MIP-for-life of the loan is a long-term cost factor; for most Directors, conventional conforming with 5&ndash;10% down is the better path.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My company is acquiring another company. Could it affect my comp?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Possibly. Acquirers sometimes issue retention RSUs to Directors at acquired companies. New grants start a new 12-month vest clock. If you&rsquo;re close to a mortgage close, finishing on current comp is usually safer; refinance later when the new grants have vest history. For senior executives with change-in-control provisions, see the <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/c-suite-executive/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">C-Suite Executive sub-page</a>.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use a pledged-asset loan against my accumulated ESPP and RSU stock?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, with sufficient accumulated portfolio. Many Directors and Senior Managers accumulate $100K&ndash;$500K+ in company stock over 5&ndash;7 years of ESPP + RSU participation. Pledged-asset loans allow you to keep that portfolio invested while using it as collateral. The trade-off: a stock price drop could trigger a margin call requiring additional collateral or partial paydown.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My base salary is $200K but I&rsquo;m being offered a Senior Director role with $260K base + larger RSU. Should I close before or after?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Two paths: (1) Close now at $200K base + current trailing comp, then refinance after the new RSU has 12-month vest history; (2) Wait and apply 13&ndash;15 months into the new role with the higher base + new RSU vest already in qualifying. Path 1 is usually safer if you have a specific home in mind; Path 2 maximizes loan capacity.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does the 401(k) match factor into qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Not directly as qualifying income &mdash; it&rsquo;s deferred compensation reported on W-2 box 12. Lenders consider it in net-worth, reserve, and asset-strength calculations. At the Director tier, the 401(k) match plus catch-up contributions (if over 50) plus profit-sharing can total $40K&ndash;$60K annually &mdash; meaningful in reserves but not in monthly qualifying income.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can my spouse&rsquo;s income combine with mine?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes. Co-borrower files combine W-2s, equity vest, bonus, and 1099 from both spouses. Dual-Director or Director + professional spouse combinations routinely support $1M&ndash;$2.5M+ purchases.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What loan amount can I qualify for at $250K of total comp?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Rough estimate: $175K base + $50K trailing 12-month RSU vest (200-day MA) + $25K bonus 2-year average = $250K annualized qualifying income. At 43% DTI and current conventional rates, that supports total monthly housing of roughly $9,000. That maps to a $900K&ndash;$1.1M mortgage depending on rate, taxes, insurance, and other debts.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My company recently IPO&rsquo;d. When can I use my new RSU income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">The 200-day moving average requires 200 trading days of stock-price history. If your company hasn&rsquo;t been public for 200 days yet, the standard calculation can&rsquo;t be applied. Fannie Mae sometimes accepts the IPO-to-date average. For pre-IPO companies, see our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/pre-ipo-equity-holder/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Pre-IPO Equity Holder sub-page</a>.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Does my company need to be publicly traded for RSU income to count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Generally yes under standard Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac rules. Public-company RSUs have a public stock price for the 200-day MA. Private-company equity is generally not eligible for conventional qualifying. Many Directors at growth-stage private companies use base + bonus alone for the mortgage, then incorporate equity after IPO.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What if my employment includes a relocation package?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Relocation gross-up payments appear on the W-2 in the year received under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p521" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRS Publication 521</a> rules. These don&rsquo;t count as continuing income (one-time event), but they do support down-payment funds if documented. For executives relocating for a new role, see also our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/relocating-executive/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Relocating Executive sub-page</a>.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use my ESPP discount as qualifying income directly?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">It&rsquo;s already in your W-2 box 1 figure on qualifying-disposition years &mdash; you don&rsquo;t add it separately. We do note ESPP participation to underwriters so they understand why box 1 may exceed base salary by $5K&ndash;$15K. Without that explanation, some underwriters reduce the W-2 by the ESPP component as "one-time" &mdash; we prevent that mis-categorization.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are mortgage rates different for Director-tier executives?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Not formally &mdash; but Director-band files often qualify for the best conventional conforming rate tier because of strong credit profiles, stable W-2, and high reserves from equity comp accumulation. We shop multiple lenders to find the optimal rate.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My role includes overtime or on-call pay. Does that count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, with a two-year history. Overtime, on-call, and shift differential pay qualify on a two-year average under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>. Underwriters sometimes discount overtime as "non-base"; with proper documentation showing the consistent pattern, the full average qualifies.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I buy a primary residence and an investment property at the same time?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, if reserves and DTI permit. Some Directors leverage accumulated equity-comp wealth to buy both a primary residence and a rental property. The rental qualifies under DSCR Non-QM rules separately. We coordinate the dual-close process.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What about multi-state tax issues if I work in one state and live in another?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Some Directors work at a corporate HQ in one state while residing in another &mdash; the situation maps to <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/861" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 861 source-of-income rules</a>. We coordinate with your tax advisor so the W-2 and state K-1 reconcile cleanly before underwriting. This is less common at the Director tier than at VP/SVP but still occurs.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can my upcoming promotion be factored into qualifying somehow?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No &mdash; underwriting is on current documented income. A promotion offer in hand (signed offer letter for higher comp) might be accepted by some lenders for a "future income" file, but most use current comp. The standard play is close on current Director comp and refinance post-promotion.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

